definition.value: A datum, measured in food calories, representing a potential amount of energy available in a food material to a consumer.
1 kilocalorie (kcal) = 1000 calories (cal). By convention in food science, the large calorie is commonly called calorie (with a capital C by some authors) to distinguish from the smaller unit.
A stalk harvested from a lemon grass plant.
A genus of plants in the mustard family (Brassicaceae). The members of the genus are informally known as cruciferous vegetables, cabbages, or mustard plants.
A steak cut of beef taken from the smaller end of the tenderloin, or psoas major of the cow carcass, usually a steer or heifer.
A butchery cut of chicken that is typically boneless.
A specific cut of chicken meat that lies under the main portion of the breast just above the ribcage around the center of the sternum. Each fillet is separated from the main breast by filament.
A fruit ripeness characteristic in which a fruit has surpassed ripeness and is undergoing decomposition.
A fruit ripeness characteristic in which a fruit has some ripe part(s) or is about to achieve full maturity.
A pome fruit of a Gala apple tree cultivar.
A cultivar of dry onion, that has a pure white papery skin and a sweet, mild white flesh.
A mild variety of onion having low sulfur content and high water content when compared to other onion varieties.
Rice flour made from brown rice and in which the bran and germ are included in the milling process.
A type of rice grown mainly in Southeast and East Asia, Northeastern India and Bhutan which has opaque grains, very low amylose content, and is especially sticky when cooked.
Flour made from glutinous rice.
Flour that has not been bleached or enriched with nutrients during the manufacturing process.
A flour is milled to a finer texture than all-purpose flour, and is made with soft wheat for a lower protein content than all-purpose flour.
A pet food that has not been heat treated or otherwise preserved.
A food item intended to provide pleasure or reward to an animal, and which might not be nutritious.
A chicken thigh that has been debonned.
A chicken thigh that has been debonned.
A carcass of a chicken that includes all anatomical parts.
A chicken carcass that has been slaughtered but not defeathered, dismembered, eviscerated, or cleaned.
This is an Uberon 'carcass' that  'has quality' some 'dead
A chicken which has been defeathered, eviscerated, and cleaned
A chicken thigh that contains skin and bone material.

A surface that contacts human food or a surface from which drainage, or other transfer, onto the food or onto a surface that contacts the food ordinarily occurs during the normal course of food processing.
A food product unsuitable to ingest by a consumer due to spoilage related to the type of product it is, or to product packaging or storage.

food that has been grown, harvested, packed, or held under such conditions that it is unfit for food; or prepared, packed, or held under insanitary conditions whereby it may have become contaminated with filth, or whereby it may have been rendered injurious to health.

Food contact materials are materials that are intended to be in contact with food. These can be things that are quite obvious like a glass or a can for soft drinks as well as machinery in a food factory or a coffee machine.
A female pig under the age of 1 year. The term is also often used to refer to a pig who has not farrowed, or given birth to a litter.
A pig between weaning and sale or transfer to the breeding herd, sold for slaughter or killed for rations.
A grower pig over 70 kg (150 lb) liveweight.
A piglet slaughtered for its tender meat.
a young pig recently separated from the sow
Organism food material that has been harvested.
A food product produced by sustainable agricultural practices.
A food product made from plant or animal cell lines incubated in a production facility.
food material that is obtained by hunting, the practice of seeking, pursuing and capturing or killing wild animals.
Food material that is obtained by foraging the natural environment.
A food product which is produced from one or more organisms, none of which have changes in their DNA as a result of genetic engineering.
A food product derived from a food fermentation process involving bacteria, yeast or mold culture.

The country or countries of manufacture, production, design, or brand origin where an article or product comes from. For multinational brands, this may include multiple countries within the value-creation process.
A product primarily manufactured in a single country of origin, and with components coming from that country.
A product primarily manufactured within America.
A single-country-of-origin product which is retailed in that country.
Food produced within a relatively short distance of where it is consumed.
A plant or plant part that is obtained by foraging the natural environment.
Cultivation of plants within a polytunnel or similar tunnel.
The rearing of domesticated animals for food.

An approach to animal husbandry designed to maximize production, while minimizing costs by keeping livestock such as cattle, poultry, and fish at high stocking densities, at large scale, and using automated feeding systems.

A technology-based approach toward food production that aims to provide optimal growing conditions throughout the development of a crop located within an enclosed growing structure such as a greenhouse or building.
